'''''Hitchcock/Truffaut''''' is a 1966 book by [[François Truffaut]] about [[Alfred Hitchcock]], originally released in French as '''''Le Cinéma selon Alfred Hitchcock'''''.<ref name="Truffaut">{{cite book|work=[[Google Books]]|authorlink=François Truffaut|title=Hitchcock/Truffaut|author=Truffaut, François|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NnE_sPb3XBQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=1983|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]}}</ref>

First published by [[Éditions Robert Laffont]], it is based on a 1962 exchange between Hitchcock and Truffaut, in which the two directors spent a week in a room at Universal Studios talking about movies. After Hitchcock's death, Truffaut updated the book with a new preface and final chapter on Hitchcock's later films.<ref name="Singer">{{cite news|url=http://screencrush.com/hitchcock-truffaut-review/|title='Hitchcock/Truffaut' Review: One of the Best Film Books of All Time Is Now a Movie|last=Singer|first=Matt|date=10 September 2015|work=Screen Crush|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>

The book is the inspiration for the 2015 documentary ''[[Hitchcock/Truffaut (film)|Hitchcock/Truffaut]]''.<ref name="IndieWire">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/bent/toronto-film-festival-adds-60-titles-including-janis-joplin-doc-and-gillian-armstrongs-women-hes-undressed-20150811 |title=Toronto Film Festival Adds 60+ Titles |accessdate=11 August 2015 |work=IndieWire}}</ref>

